The “page” package¶

The page package provides base classes and utilities to manipulate webpages using the selenium driver.

The “page” module¶

selenium_page.page contains base classes representing abstract webpages using BasePageElement data descriptor attributes. These class attributes represent various elements on the page providing an easier API for manipulating the DOM.

class selenium_page.page.BaseResultsPage(driver)[source]¶

Base class for single table results pages like Invoices, Matters, etc.

If only one data element is found in the table_data, row_objects will empty.

table_data¶

list(elements) – A list of data elements

table_headers¶

list(elements) – A list of table header elements

data_name¶

str – Name for the container class

key_field_index¶

int – Index of the field to use as the container instance’s key. Note: The objects will exist in the class instance’s ‘row_objects’ attribute.

row_objects¶

OrderedDict of namedtuple – An ordered dictionary of results objects as namedtuples. The key_field_index will be used to generate key names. If a key is duplicated, for example multiple invoice results with the same invoice number, a postfix counting the occurrences will be inserted by a unique_key_generator() so each result row maintains a unique key.

The “element” module¶

This module contains the base classes for instantiating page objects.

class selenium_page.element.BasePageElement(max_wait_time: int = 100)[source]¶

‘ Page classes use data descriptor protocol to interact with their various elements.

This is the base element data descriptor class.

All concrete BasePageElement classes must have a locator class attribute.

If the located element is a <select> a Select webelement will be used.

locator¶

The locator to select the element.

max_wait_time¶

The maximuum time to try and get an element. Defaults to 100 seconds.

Example

Consider the following element class with a made up locator object.:

class UserNameElement(BasePageElement):
    locator = 'userName'

class LoginPage(BasePage):
    username_input = UserNameElement()

login_page = LoginPage()

# The below command will set the value on the element located by the data-descriptor
login_page.username_input = 'My UserName'
Raises:TimeoutException – When the element cannot be found within the max_wait_time.
class selenium_page.element.BasePageElements(max_wait_time: int = 100)[source]¶

Similar to the above, but uses find_elements to return lists rather than find_element which returns specific nodes. Uses CSS rather than name if locator is string.

The “conditions” module¶

Selenium maintains a library of wait conditions under the support module. However, custom wait conditions can be created when none of the convenience methods fit. A custom wait condition can be created using a class with a __call__ method which reutrns False when the condition does not match.

class selenium_page.condition.LazyLoadElementHasDataCondition(locator, data_selector)[source]¶

A custom wait condition to check if the lazy loaded element has data.

locator¶

tuple – locator to find the root element, see Locators design pattern.

data_selector¶

str – css selector to find the data elements from the locator.

selenium_page.decorators.wait_until_condition(condition, timeout=10)[source]¶

Decorator to execute a function only after a condition is met.

A condition is any object with a call method returning True or False. See the LazyLoadElementHasDataCondition example.

Parameters:
  • condition (object) – The condition to check
  • timeout (int, optional) – Time in seconds before condition times out in failure

selenium_page.utils.unique_key_generator(dictionary)[source]¶

This generator object creates unique keys for the target dictionary.

If the key already exists in the dictionary it appends the number of occurrences to the key name. Useful when creating search results identifiers.

Parameters:dictionary (dict) – The target dictionary to check
Yields:str – A unique key name
